    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-10T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-10T01:00:00-05:00" n="113"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d113">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8700: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-10T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 10, 1937—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 6:06 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>260. Our July 10, 10 [<hi rend="italic">11</hi>] a.m. and third paragraph,<note
                        n="58" xml:id="d113fn58">Paragraph 3 refers to telegram No. 258, July 10 10
                        a.m., <ref target="#pg_130">p. 130</ref>.</note> July 10, 11 [<hi
                        rend="italic">10</hi>] a.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Hidaka called on Wang before noon. We are informed by a reported to be
                        reliable source [that] (1) Hidaka (under instructions from his Government)
                        and Wang expressed to each other the hope <pb facs="0143" n="136"
                            xml:id="pg_136"/> that the incident would be brought speedily to an
                        amicable settlement, and (2) Hidaka expressed on behalf of his Government
                        the further hope that the Chinese Government would take whatever steps might
                        be required to prevent any recrudescence of anti-Japanese feeling as a
                        result of the incident.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>To the Department, Peiping and Tokyo. By mail to Shanghai.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
